title: PM Albanese reflects on ‘darkest week’ in Australia’s recent history
description: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese reflects on the “darkest week” in Australia’s recent history, following the Bondi massacre.  “Australia will not allow these evil anti-Semitic terrorists to divide us, no matter how dark things were and continue to be,” Mr Albanese said.  “Light will triumph, and that's what Hannukkah is about.”

title: New funding for Bondi lifesavers: Anthony Albanese
description: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese announces new funding for Bondi life-saving clubs.  “They used up a lot of their resources in responding to the crisis that we saw last Sunday," Mr Albanese said.  “I'm deeply proud, indeed, of every hero, as I'm sure every Australian should be, who saved lives.  “In time, we will make sure they're appropriately recognised.” ​

title: Albanese supports US strikes on ISIS in Syria
description: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese comments on the US military launching air strikes on ISIS targets in Syria.  “The actions of the US government are timely, swift and decisive, and we support those actions,” Mr Albanese said.  “ISIS has caused untold suffering around the world … through their evil ideology that they spread.  “That evil ideology represents something that should have no place in any consideration of humanity.”

title: Australians to ‘stand as one’ with the Jewish community: Ed Husic
description: Labor MP Ed Husic urges Australians to “stand as one” with the Jewish community, following the Bondi terror attack.  “Antisemitism isn't a fight just for Jewish Australians to undergo; we all stand with them, we're all going to take this one on together,” Mr Husic told Sky News Australia.  “People deserve, as I've said many times, to live a life free from fear, free to be who they are, free to practice their faith, and free to be Australian.  “One and all.”

title: Prime minister backs NSW premier’s call for a royal commission into Bondi attack
description: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese responds to NSW Premier Chris Minns calling for a Royal Commission into the Bondi attack.  “What we are continuing to do at this point is to act,” Mr Albanese said.  “I will support whatever actions the NSW government takes.”

title: ‘Weak government’: Frydenberg blasts Jacinta Allan for 'inaction' against antisemitism
description: Former treasurer Josh Frydenberg claims “inaction” against antisemitism has taken place in Victoria “under Jacinta Allan’s watch.”  “Now is a time for action,” Mr Frydenberg told Sky News Australia.  “The Premier of Victoria, as the Prime Minister of Australia, has been judged by their inaction.”

title: Albanese hiding behind ‘weasel words’ on ‘festering’ antisemitism
description: Former NSW senator Hollie Hughes claims that Anthony Albanese has no idea how to address the “festering” antisemitism in Australia.  “Someone with some guts needs to put a motion up when they get back to parliament calling for a no-confidence motion in this prime minister,” Ms Hughes told Sky News host Rowan Dean.  “Let’s see who backs it and who doesn’t.”

title: Josh Frydenberg: ‘Bad things happen when good people stay silent’
description: Former treasurer Josh Frydenberg claims the Bondi Beach attack has sparked a “tipping point” for the government to take the necessary action.  “Bad things happen when good people stay silent,” Mr Frydenberg told Sky News Australia.  “Globalise the intifada we hear, in chants on our harbor bridge.”   If Anthony Albanese “doesn’t take strong action to protect our citizens, then who does he expect to do that?”

title: Labor blasted for ‘normalising’ extreme and radical views in Australian protests
description: NSW Independent MP Tania Mihailuk claims members of the government have ‘normalised’ extreme and radical views in Australian protests.  “What we need to be focused on is protests that are inciting hatred,” Ms Mihailuk told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “Members of the government have normalised this.”

title: Jewish leaders warn of Melbourne protest ‘against measures to counter antisemitism’
description: Former treasurer Josh Frydenberg says it’s “unthinkable” the Vic government would allow a “demonstration against strong measures to counter antisemitism” to go ahead.  “Tell me in any way does this enhance our social cohesion?” Mr Frydenberg told Sky News Australia.   “All it does is pour petrol on the fire of hate.”

title: ‘No confidence’: Joyce blasts Albanese for ‘leaving a huge gap in the security’ of Australia
description: One Nation MP Barnaby Joyce claims that Anthony Albanese's “judgement” has left a huge gap in Australia’s national security.  “We’ve got no confidence in him,” Mr Joyce told Sky News host Rowan Dean.  “His capacity to carry his office of Prime Minister has been found wanting and leaving a huge gap in the security of our nation.”

title: ‘History will remember this’: Radical leftists’ tone-deaf vigil days after Bondi attack
description: Spiked Chief Political Writer Brendan O’Neill claims “history will remember” radical leftists who held a vigil in London for Palestine Action days after the Bondi attack.  Mr O’Neill told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio that leftists “claim to be anti-racist, they claim to be anti-fascist.”  “Yet they have nothing to say.”

title: ‘Debt will continue to increase’: Revenue growth to be met by equal spending growth
description: Emminence Advisory’s Dimitri Burshtein discusses 2025-26 MYEFO showing improvement to the federal budget.  “The claim the budget and economy are improving isn’t technically a lie,” Mr Burshtein told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “It’s simply something the treasurer seems to believe.”

title: Astrologists at odds over an interstellar object passing earth
description: Astrologists are at odds about the nature of an interstellar object passing earth.  Some experts are suggesting the object may be related to extraterrestrial life.  Oxford University Astrophysicist Professor Chris Lintott says there is nothing "that suggests alien life, that suggests intelligence, that suggests this is anything other than a comet.”

title: Food relief charity gives aid to communities before the Christmas season
description: Many in our communities are relying on the kindness of others to bring joy this Christmas.   With a cost-of-living crisis making essential items unaffordable, food relief takes some pressure off those doing it tough.  The True You Club community shop is one way donors can make a difference.
